{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c3321123-bdbd-4b99-91ad-f815fe9c1370","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can tell you exactly what you need to configure to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org.\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\nAdd these to your `MyMcpServer.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Mark as a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet package metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n\n<!-- Include a README in the package -->\n<ItemGroup>\n  <None Include=\"README.md\" Pack=\"true\" PackagePath=\"/\" />\n</ItemGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n- **`PackAsTool`** — this is the critical property that makes `dotnet tool install` work.\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`).\n- **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — required for both stdio transport and dotnet tools.\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from https://www.nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server   # runs via stdio\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"885a989e-64c7-4858-bf2d-953e69095154","outputTokens":525,"requestId":"1589:E621D:318AFF6:363DB52:69FBE61D"},"id":"47c70e06-a09a-49d4-bb27-c2d4a8ddb841","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:08:55.028Z","parentId":"53d3b759-7e30-4db1-84ed-a8850ae77be0"}
